WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.480
Hi, I'm Garrick Aden-Buie, a data science educator at RStudio and an R and Shiny developer.

00:00:11.480 --> 00:00:15.600
I also tinker with web development, and I realize that I've learned the most about web

00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:18.480
development by working on my slides.

00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:22.040
Wanting to put images in the right place or give text the right color, it's like each

00:00:22.040 --> 00:00:26.400
slide ends up becoming a small web project, and I've learned more about web development

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:28.120
this way than any other.

00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:30.120
So that's what I want to share with you today.

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:34.480
How can we use xaringan as a playground to learn web development?

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:35.759
So wait, what?

00:00:35.759 --> 00:00:37.200
What is xaringan?

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:40.439
First of all, it's an R package that you can install from Crayon.

00:00:40.439 --> 00:00:44.860
Second, it's a way to write an R markdown with some extra syntax, and then have your

00:00:44.860 --> 00:00:50.360
R markdown, R code, and outputs, plots, widgets, all rendered into slides.

00:00:50.360 --> 00:00:55.040
The slides are web pages in HTML, and the great thing about that is that you can use

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:57.740
CSS to layout and style your slides.

00:00:57.740 --> 00:01:02.419
But the downside is that you have to use CSS to layout and style your slides.

00:01:02.419 --> 00:01:06.580
So CSS is a little tricky to wrap your mind around, but I think that xaringan makes it

00:01:06.580 --> 00:01:08.040
a little more fun.

00:01:08.040 --> 00:01:12.059
So let's first learn a little bit about CSS and the web.

00:01:12.059 --> 00:01:16.199
CSS styles are rules about how elements on the screen should appear.

00:01:16.199 --> 00:01:20.260
The most common way to link a rule to an element is to use a class.

00:01:20.260 --> 00:01:23.180
In CSS, these start with a dot.

00:01:23.180 --> 00:01:27.699
Xaringan has an extra little syntax that makes it easier to reference these CSS classes.

00:01:27.699 --> 00:01:31.900
You write the class name, then a pair of brackets, and then you put text or whatever

00:01:31.900 --> 00:01:34.059
you want inside the brackets.

00:01:34.059 --> 00:01:39.019
Here we use the complement class for the whole sentence, and the RStudioBlue class for just

00:01:39.019 --> 00:01:41.620
the word RStudio.

00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:47.220
Inside a rule, there are CSS properties where you can set a property equal to a value, like

00:01:47.220 --> 00:01:51.980
font family to monospace, or color to tomato.

00:01:51.980 --> 00:01:56.900
Notice that because RStudioBlue has its own color, and it's closer to the word RStudio,

00:01:56.900 --> 00:01:58.339
it wraps around RStudio.

00:01:58.339 --> 00:02:01.379
It doesn't turn tomato.

00:02:01.379 --> 00:02:05.099
The second thing to know about the web is that everything is in a box.

00:02:05.099 --> 00:02:09.020
The block boxes take up a full line of horizontal space.

00:02:09.020 --> 00:02:12.899
In Markdown, their brackets span more than one line.

00:02:12.899 --> 00:02:16.880
Inline boxes fit within block boxes and don't break the flow.

00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:21.160
In Markdown, their brackets are on the same line, like with RStudioBlue.

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:25.100
The real reason xaringan is so fun is infinite moon reader.

00:02:25.100 --> 00:02:27.259
Let me show you why.

00:02:27.259 --> 00:02:31.339
Okay, I have a little project here with some slides.

00:02:31.339 --> 00:02:34.619
It's an RMD file, and I've cleared out all of the starter text.

00:02:34.619 --> 00:02:37.979
So let's add a heading and render the slides.

00:02:37.979 --> 00:02:39.479
Great.

00:02:39.479 --> 00:02:41.860
But now let's use infinite moon reader.

00:02:41.860 --> 00:02:44.380
It's available under the add-ins menu.

00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:47.619
When we run it, it first renders the slides.

00:02:47.619 --> 00:02:51.380
But when I type, my text shows up right away.

00:02:51.380 --> 00:02:53.100
This is awesome.

00:02:53.100 --> 00:02:56.139
So let's recreate the example we saw in the slides.

00:02:56.139 --> 00:02:59.820
I have a compliment that RStudio is cool.

00:02:59.820 --> 00:03:02.220
And I'll put RStudio in RStudioBlue.

00:03:02.220 --> 00:03:05.259
Okay, that takes care of the Markdown.

00:03:05.259 --> 00:03:09.460
But we can add HTML to the slides too, which means I can create a style block and create

00:03:09.460 --> 00:03:15.179
rules for the compliment in RStudioBlue color.

00:03:15.179 --> 00:03:20.779
Look, the slides are updated live.

00:03:20.779 --> 00:03:22.940
Are we having fun?

00:03:23.300 --> 00:03:27.020
Classes are reusable, so let's make fun blue too.

00:03:27.020 --> 00:03:29.740
Okay, one more example.

00:03:29.740 --> 00:03:32.940
Let's create a block element called cat box.

00:03:32.940 --> 00:03:35.380
In the box, we'll put a cat.

00:03:35.380 --> 00:03:39.460
It's hard to see the block element, so let's give it a background color.

00:03:39.460 --> 00:03:41.580
Now you can see it takes up the whole line.

00:03:41.580 --> 00:03:47.660
And let's give it a height and a width, say 300 pixels each.

00:03:47.660 --> 00:03:52.580
And rather than have it be a blue background, let's actually put a cat in the box.

00:03:52.580 --> 00:03:58.460
For this, we can use background image with URL, and then a URL to a placeholder kitten

00:03:58.460 --> 00:04:00.380
image.

00:04:00.380 --> 00:04:04.899
Now usually cats on slides are positioned off to the side a bit, and we can do this

00:04:04.899 --> 00:04:05.899
too.

00:04:05.899 --> 00:04:10.539
We'll set position to absolute, which tells the browser to put the box exactly where we

00:04:10.539 --> 00:04:16.220
want it to be, relative to the top, right, bottom, or left of the box's container, which

00:04:16.220 --> 00:04:17.859
is our slide.

00:04:17.859 --> 00:04:23.540
So let's put it about 50 pixels from the bottom, and 50 pixels from the right.

00:04:23.540 --> 00:04:24.820
Great.

00:04:24.820 --> 00:04:30.980
One last note, when you're done, you should put these styles in a CSS file.

00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:38.779
Okay, I hope you enjoyed this and learned a little.

00:04:38.779 --> 00:04:40.299
Go explore and have fun.

00:04:40.299 --> 00:04:42.100
And also, check out Scheringen Extra.

00:04:42.100 --> 00:04:46.059
It's an R package that brings lots of little goodies to Scheringen.

00:04:46.059 --> 00:04:47.140
Go make great slides.

00:04:48.660 --> 00:04:49.660
Bye.

00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:50.660
Bye.

00:04:50.660 --> 00:04:50.660


